---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { profile } from '../data/portfolio';

const title = 'FlexSync — Bidirectional Shopify ↔ Google Sheets sync · Kazi Badrul';
const description =
  'Case study: a solo-built public Shopify app that keeps a merchant\'s catalog in two-way sync with Google Sheets — 400+ merchants, 4M+ requests a month, built on a serialized bulk-operation queue and buffered webhook processing.';

const stat = [
  { num: '4M+', label: 'requests / month' },
  { num: '400+', label: 'merchants in production' },
  { num: '60%', label: 'sync latency cut' },
  { num: '1', label: 'engineer — solo-built' },
];

const stack = [
  'Laravel 12', 'React 18', 'TypeScript', 'MySQL', 'Redis',
  'Shopify GraphQL Admin API', 'Bulk Operations API', 'Google Sheets API', 'Apps Script',
];
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
  <nav class="nav">
    <div class="wrap">
      <a href="/" class="logo">kazi<span class="dot">.</span>badrul</a>
      <div class="nav-links">
        <a href="/#work">← all work</a>
        <a href="/#contact">contact</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <main class="cs">
    <!-- HERO -->
    <header class="cs-hero">
      <div class="wrap">
        <a class="back" href="/#work">← Back to work</a>
        <div class="eyebrow">case study · Shopify public app</div>
        <h1>FlexSync</h1>
        <p class="cs-lede">
          A public Shopify app that keeps a merchant's product catalog in
          <strong>continuous two-way sync with Google Sheets</strong> — export products,
          variants, and inventory into a spreadsheet, bulk-edit them where merchants already
          work, and push every change back to Shopify without the two systems ever drifting apart.
        </p>

        <div class="cs-meta">
          <div><span class="k">Role</span><span class="v">Sole engineer · WPPOOL</span></div>
          <div><span class="k">Timeline</span><span class="v">2023 — present</span></div>
          <div><span class="k">Surface</span><span class="v">Published on the Shopify App Store</span></div>
          <div><span class="k">Ownership</span><span class="v">Architecture → backend → frontend → ship</span></div>
        </div>

        <div class="cs-stats">
          {stat.map((s) => (
            <div class="cs-stat">
              <div class="num gradient-text">{s.num}</div>
              <div class="label">{s.label}</div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        <div class="cs-tags">
          {stack.map((s) => <span class="tag">{s}</span>)}
        </div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="wrap cs-body">
      <!-- PROBLEM -->
      <section class="cs-section">
        <div class="eyebrow">the problem</div>
        <h2>Merchants live in spreadsheets. Shopify doesn't.</h2>
        <p>
          Store operators run their catalog in Google Sheets — pricing rules, supplier
          stock feeds, seasonal bulk edits, VLOOKUPs against a wholesale list. But Shopify's
          admin is a one-record-at-a-time UI, and its CSV import/export is a lossy,
          fire-and-forget round trip: you export, edit offline, re-import, and pray nothing
          collided while you were away.
        </p>
        <p>
          There was no dependable <em>live</em> bridge. Merchants wanted the spreadsheet to be a
          real working surface — edit a price in a cell and have Shopify reflect it; sell a unit on
          Shopify and have the sheet reflect it — with neither side silently overwriting the other.
          That's a distributed two-way sync problem hiding behind a friendly &ldquo;just a spreadsheet&rdquo; UX,
          and the hard parts are all the ones a merchant never sees.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- WHAT I BUILT -->
      <section class="cs-section">
        <div class="eyebrow">what i built</div>
        <h2>One app, two directions, no drift.</h2>
        <p>
          FlexSync is a Laravel + React public app that installs on a store, connects a Google
          Sheet, and then keeps the two in agreement continuously. A merchant works entirely in
          the spreadsheet they already know; FlexSync owns the messy middle — rate limits, async
          bulk jobs, webhook fan-in, conflict resolution, and echo suppression so an update never
          bounces back and forth forever.
        </p>
        <ul class="cs-list">
          <li><strong>Shopify → Sheets.</strong> Full-catalog export of products, variants, inventory, and metafields into a structured sheet, then incremental updates as the store changes.</li>
          <li><strong>Sheets → Shopify.</strong> Edits in the spreadsheet — including live spreadsheet formulas for price and stock — resolve to values and push back to Shopify.</li>
          <li><strong>Formula sync.</strong> A merchant can write <span class="mono">=cost*1.4</span> in a price cell; FlexSync evaluates it and writes the result to Shopify, so pricing logic lives where the merchant already keeps it.</li>
          <li><strong>Passive by default.</strong> Once connected, it just stays correct — no manual re-import, no &ldquo;click to sync&rdquo; ritual.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- ARCHITECTURE -->
      <section class="cs-section">
        <div class="eyebrow">how it works</div>
        <h2>The engineering under the spreadsheet.</h2>

        <div class="cs-block">
          <h3>A serialized bulk-operation queue</h3>
          <p>
            Shopify's Admin API is cost-based and aggressively rate-limited, and bulk reads/writes
            run as <em>asynchronous</em> jobs you poll for completion. A naive &ldquo;fire a mutation per
            row&rdquo; design dies instantly at catalog scale. FlexSync routes every write through a
            serialized, per-shop queue on Laravel + Redis: work is batched into Bulk Operations,
            only one bulk job per store is ever in flight, and the queue backs off and resumes
            around Shopify's throttle instead of hammering into it.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="cs-block">
          <h3>Buffered, webhook-driven updates — 60% less latency</h3>
          <p>
            Store-side changes arrive as webhooks. Rather than process each one synchronously,
            FlexSync buffers bursts and coalesces them: ten edits to the same product in a few
            seconds collapse into one downstream sync instead of ten. That buffering is where the
            <strong>60% sync-latency reduction</strong> came from — less redundant work on the hot path,
            fewer API calls spent, and a system that stays responsive during bulk store activity.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="cs-block">
          <h3>Drift and echo prevention</h3>
          <p>
            The core hazard in any two-way sync is the feedback loop: FlexSync writes to Shopify,
            Shopify fires a webhook, FlexSync reads it as a &ldquo;new&rdquo; change and writes it back — forever.
            I solved that with change-origin tracking and version stamping so the engine recognizes
            its own echoes and drops them, and applies a deterministic resolution rule when both sides
            move at once. The two systems converge instead of oscillating.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="cs-block">
          <h3>Scaling to 4M+ requests a month</h3>
          <p>
            At 400+ live stores, webhook plus user traffic crossed several million requests a month.
            The scaling work was unglamorous and effective: MySQL index optimization on the hot sync
            and lookup paths, keeping the queue serialized per shop so no single store could starve
            the rest, and pushing everything that didn't need to be synchronous off the request path.
            It holds that volume on modest infrastructure.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- RESULTS -->
      <section class="cs-section">
        <div class="eyebrow">results</div>
        <h2>What shipped, and what it moved.</h2>
        <ul class="cs-list">
          <li><strong>400+ merchants</strong> running it in production against their live catalogs.</li>
          <li><strong>4M+ requests a month</strong> handled — webhooks and user traffic — on a serialized queue.</li>
          <li><strong>60% lower sync latency</strong> after moving to buffered, coalesced webhook processing.</li>
          <li><strong>Formula sync</strong> shipped — a feature merchants specifically asked for, because it let their pricing logic stay in the sheet.</li>
          <li><strong>5★ App Store reviews</strong> that call out the support as much as the product.</li>
        </ul>

        <figure class="cs-quote">
          <blockquote>
            &ldquo;Super helpful app and passionate, supportive developers. They really spent time trying
            to solve an issue for me when they didn't have to! Thanks so much!&rdquo;
          </blockquote>
          <figcaption>lizfrydesign · 5★ review, Shopify App Store</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </section>

      <!-- WHAT IT DEMONSTRATES -->
      <section class="cs-section">
        <div class="eyebrow">the takeaway</div>
        <h2>Why this project is the one I lead with.</h2>
        <p>
          FlexSync is a distributed-systems problem — idempotency, rate limits, async job
          orchestration, conflict resolution, convergence — wearing a spreadsheet's clothes. I
          owned all of it: the architecture, the Laravel backend, the React frontend, the Shopify
          and Google integrations, and the operational reality of keeping 400+ stores correct
          every day. Solo, in production, on a narrow stack, under real constraints.
        </p>
        <p>
          That's the signal I care about: not a feature list, but ownership and shipping under
          constraint — the same thing I'd bring to an early team.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- CTA -->
      <section class="cs-cta">
        <h2>Want the deeper walkthrough?</h2>
        <p>Happy to whiteboard the queue design, the webhook buffering, or the drift-prevention model.</p>
        <div class="cta-row">
          <a class="btn btn-primary" href={`mailto:${profile.email}`}>Get in touch</a>
          <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/#work">← Back to work</a>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>
  </main>

  <footer>
    <div class="wrap">
      <span>© 2026 {profile.name}</span>
      <span>Built with Astro · deployed on Cloudflare Pages</span>
    </div>
  </footer>
</Layout>

<style>
  .cs-hero {
    padding: 72px 0 48px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    background:
      radial-gradient(50rem 30rem at 90% -10%, rgba(129, 140, 248, 0.10), transparent 60%),
      radial-gradient(40rem 30rem at 0% 0%, rgba(94, 234, 212, 0.06), transparent 55%);
  }
  .back {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 13px;
    color: var(--text-dim);
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: 24px;
    transition: color 0.15s;
  }
  .back:hover { color: var(--accent); }
  .cs-hero h1 {
    font-size: clamp(44px, 9vw, 84px);
    font-weight: 800;
    letter-spacing: -0.04em;
    line-height: 1;
    margin: 0 0 22px;
  }
  .cs-lede {
    font-size: clamp(17px, 2.3vw, 21px);
    color: var(--text-dim);
    max-width: 720px;
    margin: 0 0 40px;
    line-height: 1.55;
  }
  .cs-lede strong { color: var(--text); font-weight: 600; }

  .cs-meta {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: 18px 40px;
    max-width: 720px;
    padding: 24px 0;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    margin-bottom: 36px;
  }
  @media (max-width: 620px) { .cs-meta { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
  .cs-meta div { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 4px; }
  .cs-meta .k {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 11px;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--text-faint);
  }
  .cs-meta .v { font-size: 14.5px; color: var(--text); }

  .cs-stats {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 40px;
    margin-bottom: 32px;
  }
  .cs-stat .num {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 32px;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.03em;
  }
  .cs-stat .label { font-size: 12.5px; color: var(--text-faint); font-family: var(--mono); }

  .cs-tags { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 7px; }

  .cs-body { padding-bottom: 40px; }
  .cs-section { padding: 64px 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .cs-section:last-of-type { border-bottom: none; }
  .cs-section h2 {
    font-size: clamp(24px, 3.6vw, 34px);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.03em;
    margin: 0 0 22px;
    max-width: 760px;
  }
  .cs-section > p {
    color: var(--text-dim);
    max-width: 760px;
    margin: 0 0 18px;
    font-size: 16px;
  }
  .cs-section em { color: var(--text); font-style: italic; }
  .cs-section strong { color: var(--text); font-weight: 600; }

  .cs-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 8px 0 0;
    max-width: 760px;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 14px;
  }
  .cs-list li {
    position: relative;
    padding-left: 26px;
    color: var(--text-dim);
    font-size: 15.5px;
    line-height: 1.55;
  }
  .cs-list li::before {
    content: "→";
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    top: 0;
    color: var(--accent);
  }
  .cs-list .mono {
    background: var(--bg-soft);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 1px 7px;
    font-size: 13.5px;
    color: var(--accent);
  }

  .cs-block {
    border-left: 2px solid var(--border-bright);
    padding: 4px 0 4px 24px;
    margin: 28px 0;
    max-width: 780px;
  }
  .cs-block h3 {
    font-size: 18px;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    margin: 0 0 10px;
    color: var(--text);
  }
  .cs-block p { color: var(--text-dim); margin: 0; font-size: 15.5px; line-height: 1.6; }

  .cs-quote {
    margin: 32px 0 0;
    padding: 28px 30px;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 16px;
    background: var(--panel);
    position: relative;
    max-width: 760px;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .cs-quote::after {
    content: "";
    position: absolute;
    left: 0; top: 0; bottom: 0;
    width: 3px;
    background: var(--grad);
  }
  .cs-quote blockquote {
    margin: 0 0 14px;
    font-size: 18px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    color: var(--text);
  }
  .cs-quote figcaption {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 12px;
    color: var(--text-faint);
  }

  .cs-cta { padding: 72px 0 24px; text-align: center; }
  .cs-cta h2 {
    font-size: clamp(26px, 4vw, 40px);
    letter-spacing: -0.03em;
    margin: 0 0 14px;
  }
  .cs-cta p { color: var(--text-dim); max-width: 480px; margin: 0 auto 28px; }
  .cs-cta .cta-row { justify-content: center; }
</style>
